Drought Data Exploration & QC Flags

Ashley Vizek

2024-04-04

Document purpose

The goal of this document is to summarize the data collated to support the Drought Communications Data and Tool Project which aims to create publicly available and easily accessible data and tools to track drought risk, potential impacts, and actions that can reduce risks and impacts.

The data needed to support this project come from disparate sources with varying levels of quality, accessibility, and usability.

Status: This is a first draft of pulling the data needed, and documenting quality issues. This work will inform data processing that will be required, and processes for data pulling and updating.

Summary of data tables

The following data tables are drafted. Metadata associated with each of these tables is included in the following section.

  • monthly dry outlook
  • drought risk assessment
  • water shortage level
  • production and delivery volumes
  • number of supply sources
  • name of supply sources
  • population

The following data tables have not been drafted and exist as placeholders.

  • pwsid crosswalk
  • drought risk assessment narrative
  • water shortage contingency plan narrative
  • water source location

Metadata by data table

The following information is provided in the metadata tables:

  • Where do data come from?
  • What type of data pull is available?
  • What is the goal of the data?
  • Data dictionary

monthly dry year outlook

Goal: Answer the question, are we going to run out of water in the near-term? Provide dry year outlook of water surplus or shortage by month (where available) with no action and with planned actions.

Existing data source: WUE_WSDA

Available data pull type: scraping

attribute_name description format definitions
ORG_ID DWR_ORG_ID ID N/A
YEAR Future outlook year INTEGER 2022:2023
MONTH Month VARCHAR "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec", "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun"
SHORTAGE_TYPE Describes whether the surplus/shortage volume is associated with no action or with augmentation/demand reducation action VARCHAR "supply augmentation", "demand reduction", "no action"
ACRE_FEET Volume of surplus/shortage water in acre-feet. If volume was reported in another unit it was converted to acre-feet NUMERIC N/A

drought risk assessment

Goal: Answer the question, are we going to run out of water in the next five years? Provide outlook of water surplus or shortage by month (where available) and year with no action and with planned actions.

Existing data source: WUE_UWMP

Available data pull type: scraping

attribute_name description format definitions
ORG_ID DWR_ORG_ID ID N/A
YEAR Year associated with water volume projections INTEGER 2001:2025
IS_ACTION_INCLUDED Describes whether the surplus/shortage volume is associated with no action or with augmentation/demand reducation action BOOLEAN T/F
ACRE_FEET Volume of surplus/shortage water in acre-feet. If volume was reported in another unit it was converted to acre-feet NUMERIC N/A

water shortage level

Goal: Provide the current water shortage level and history of water shortage by month.

Existing data source: ODP_CR

Available data pull type: API

attribute_name description format definitions
PWSID PWSID ID N/A
YEAR Reporting year INTEGER NA
MONTH Reporting month VARCHAR "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec", "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun"
WATER_SHORTAGE_STAGE Describes the water shortage stage; however, these levels are not standardized and currently not usable. NA Too many unique levels!!
SHORTAGE_GREATER_10_PERCENT Flags if shortage level is greater than 10% (T) or not (F) LOGICAL T/F
DWR_WATER_SHORTAGE_STAGE Standardized shortage stage; however, this only applies to 2022-2023 data. INTEGER 0-5

SOURCE_NAME Name of water supply source STRING NA

PRODUCED_OR_DELIVERY_TYPE Describes the specific type of demand or supply VARCHAR "commercial/institutional", "multi-family residential", "landscape irrigation", "other", "other pws", "agriculture", "total retail", "single-family residential", "industrial", "groundwater wells", "purchased or received from another pws", "sold to another pws", "total amount of potable water", "non-potable (total excluded recycled)", "recycled", "surface water", "non-potable water sold to another pws"

Data exploration

monthly dry year outlook

Reporting annually rather than monthly

There was a concern that not all may be reporting by month though this not appear to be an issue in the 2022 data when you look at missing values. There are no missing values. However, when you look at similarity of the Annual value reported and the value reported by month this is where you can differentiate which are reporting annually.

There is no missing information by month for surplus/shortage with no action. However, not all have demand or augementation actions so there are NAs. About 60% of DWR_ORG_ID respond as NA for demand reduction actions and 80% for supply augmentation.

  • Decision point - retain these as NAs or include as 0

Plot: Percent of DWR_ID with NA response by type and month

Summarizing surplus or shortage

Some of the questions that can be answered with this data:

  • In what months do shortages occur and in what months do surplus occur?
  • Do suppliers that anticipate shortages implement actions to counteract?
  • Are there any cases where there are shortages and no actions implemented?
  • Are there similarities in suppliers that consistently have shortages/surpluses?

The high level overview shows that the most commonly reported value is 0. There are a couple things that could be going on - suppliers are experiencing different magnitudes by month and so small values are being dwarfed by larger outliers; the monthly trend differs by supplier; there are lots of 0s in the dataset.

Currently visualizing this data is not that helpful. Future work can be done to create groups of suppliers to better see variation. Shortage/surplus could also be presented as a percentage of total demand to help normalize across suppliers.

Plot: Variation in surplus/shortage volume by type

Comparing data across years

Initial review reveals that there are differences across years and the same value is not repeated for each year. To identify trends or patterns would require additional analysis.

  • What years are included in this data?

Note that it is difficult to tease apart whether data is really by month. Often the responses are the same across months within the year which may reflect the real monthly shortage level or the same value may be reported across months.

Summary of QC issues

1. monthly dry outlook

  • Values being reported by month for some and annually for others
  • NAs for the supply augmentation or demand reduction where no action implemented
  • Surplus/shortage are not normalized so makes it challenging to interpret these summarized data
  • Annual is included in these data so need to figure out how to handle that

2. drought risk assessment

  • 4 cases where DWR_ORG_ID is NA
  • There are cases where there is a volume shortage even when actions are applied. Are these QC issues or real?
  • These data are very different than the values reported in the 2022 dry year outlook. Why?

3. water shortage

  • DWR_WATER_SHORTAGE_STAGE represents the standardized water shortage level though is only available for 2022-2023. WATER_SHORTAGE_STAGE is not usable currently and needs to be mapped to the standardized levels.
  • Uncertainty whether the data represents real monthly values or the same value is reported for each month.

4. source name

  • Extracting usable information from these data is still in progress

5. number of sources

  • Are NAs real NAs meaning that the particular water source does not apply? If so, we could use this information. If not, we should transform to 0.
  • Is there a definition for what is considered a unique water source?

6. production and delivery volumes

  • Annual values are included so need to figure out how to handle that
  • The dataset provided by Rafa does not seem to be complete
